  1. (5pt) Make a plot of total CO2 emissions over time for the U.S, China, and India. Add a few more countries of your choice. Explain what do you see.
co2_plot <- df %>% group_by(name) %>% summarise(total_co2 = sum(co2,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% filter(name == "United States of America" | name =="China" | name == "India" | name == "Japan" | name == "Australia")

ggplot(data = co2_plot, aes(y = total_co2, x = name ))+ geom_bar(stat="identity")

US has the most total CO2 emissions over time, China has the second most, then is Japan, India, and Australia. US and Chinas total CO2 emissions are significantly higher than the other three countriess.

  1. (5pt) Now lets analyze the CO2 emissions per capita (co2_PC ). Make a similar plot of the same countries. What does this figure suggest?
co2PC_plot <- df %>% group_by(name) %>% summarise(total_co2PC = sum(co2_PC,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% filter(name == "United States of America" | name =="China" | name == "India" | name == "Japan" | name == "Australia")

ggplot(data = co2PC_plot, aes(y = total_co2PC, x = name ))+ geom_bar(stat="identity")

US has the most total CO2 emissions per capita, but this time Australia has the second most, then is Japan, China, and India. Since now CO2 is caculated by per capita, it make sense that country has larger population has less CO2 emissions per capita.

  1. (8pt) Compute the average LE growth from 1960-2019 across the continents. Show the results in the order of growth. Explain what do you see. Hint: these data (data in long form) is not the simplest to compute growth. But you may want to check out the lag() function. And do not forget to group data by continent when using lag(), otherwise your results will be messed up! See https://faculty.washington. edu/otoomet/info201-book/dplyr.html#dplyr-helpers-compute.
df %>% group_by(region, time) %>% summarise(avgLE = mean(lifeExpectancy, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% mutate(prevLE = lag(avgLE), growth = avgLE - prevLE)
